==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|acidité}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|aciditātem}}, accusative singular of {{m|la|aciditās||sourness, acidity}}, from {{m|la|acidus||sour, acid}}. See {{m|en|acid}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/əˈsɪdɪti/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-acidity.wav|Audio (RP)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The [[quality]] or state of being acid.
# [[sourness|Sourness]]; [[tartness]]; [[sharpness]] to the taste.
#: {{ux|en|the '''acidity''' of lemon juice}}
#: {{ux|en|Empty stomachs lead to '''acidity''' and leave a sour taste in the mouth.}}
# {{lb|en|pathology}} Excessive acid quality, as in [[gastric]] [[secretion|secretions]].
# {{lb|en|figurative}} A [[caustic]], [[sour]], [[biting]], or [[bitter]] quality.
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1912|author=Sir Arthur Conan Doyle|authorlink=Arthur Conan Doyle|title=The Lost World|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/139/pg139.txt|passage="What shall we call it?" he asked. "Why should you not take the chance of perpetuating your own name?" said Summerlee, with his usual touch of '''acidity'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1913|author=Sir Arthur Conan Doyle|authorlink=Arthur Conan Doyle|title=The Poison Belt|page=60|passage=It was a brave, good speech, a speech from that staunch and strong spirit which lay behind all the '''acidities''' and angularities of the old zoologist.}}

